SUMMARY:Revolutionizing Gender Norms in the 18th Century
DESCRIPTION:A Rev250 & Pride Month Program\n\nfeaturing Meg Bowersox\, 
 Museum of the American Revolution\n\nDuring the American Revolution\, some 
 people seized the opportunity to challenge gender identity and other social 
 norms of the period. In this thought-provoking lecture\, Meg Bowersox of 
 the Museum of the American Revolution will discuss The Public Universal 
 Friend\, Deborah Sampson\, and others of the era who bent or broke gender 
 norms\, examining how their stories fit into the larger history of the 
 LGBTQIA  movement in the United States.\n\nAbout the presenter\n\nMeg 
 Bowersox is the Manager of Gallery Interpretation at the Museum of the 
 American Revolution in Philadelphia. Meg earned her Master’s in Museum 
 Education from The University of the Arts and holds a Bachelor of Fine Arts 
 from William Patterson University. Through its collection\, immersive 
 galleries\, theater experiences\, and interactive elements the Museum of 
 the American Revolution aims to uncover and share compelling stories about 
 the diverse people and complex events that sparked America’s ongoing 
 experiment in liberty\, equality\, and self-government.
LOCATION:West Orange - Community Room 1\, West Orange Public Library
ORGANIZER;CN="West Orange Library":MAILTO:events@westorange.bccls.org
CATEGORIES:Lecture
UID:LibCal-10341-16593076
URL:https://bccls.libcal.com/event/16593076
END:VEVENT
