BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART:20260625T223000Z
DTEND:20260625T233000Z
DTSTAMP:20260625T000000Z
SUMMARY:The Creative Flowering of the Beach Boys' Brian Wilson
DESCRIPTION:With Dave Gebroe\n\nBrian Wilson\, the main creative force 
 behind The Beach Boys throughout their unparalleled 1960s run\, experienced 
 a peerless creative renaissance that I believe to be the most inspiring and 
 fertile period in any artist’s life ever\, in any medium. He didn’t 
 just make his art… His art was his life. His life was his art\, his art 
 was his art\, his joy was his art\, his new friends were his art… all of 
 it together was a celebration of life\, a space he was unfortunately never 
 really able to inhabit again for various reasons: family pressure\, career 
 pressure\, drugs\, mental illness\, and the expectations that come along 
 with being a genius. This presentation\, which combines a lecture with 
 music and interview clips from my podcast\, explores the 10-year period 
 from 1958 to 1968\, illustrating how Brian Wilson creatively soared and\, 
 much like the myth of Icarus\, flew directly into the sun\n\nArtist 
 information\n\nDave Gebroe is the creator and host of the music obsessives 
 podcast Discograffiti\, which has been featuring interviews with well-known 
 music luminaries for over four years. The show now ranks in the top 1.5% of 
 all podcasts globally.
LOCATION:West Orange - Community Room 1
ORGANIZER;CN="West Orange Library":MAILTO:events@westorange.bccls.org
CATEGORIES:
UID:LibCal-10341-16413206
URL:https://bccls.libcal.com/event/16413206
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART:20260626T150000Z
DTEND:20260626T160000Z
DTSTAMP:20260626T000000Z
SUMMARY:June Book Club: Violeta
DESCRIPTION:A book club for adults who want to read in community. We meet 
 one Friday morning a month to chat about a title we read in 
 common.\n\n--\nSummer World Literature Series\n\nVIOLETA \nby Isabel 
 Allende \n\nFrom the author of House of Spirits\, an epic story about a 
 woman whose life spans one hundred years and bears witness to the greatest 
 upheavals of the twentieth century. Violeta comes into the world on a 
 stormy day in 1920\, the first girl in a family with five boisterous sons. 
 From the start\, her life is marked by extraordinary events\, for the 
 ripples of the Great War are still being felt\, even as the Spanish flu 
 arrives on the shores of her South American homeland almost at the moment 
 of her birth. Violeta tells her story in the form of a letter to someone 
 she loves above all others\, recounting times of devastating heartbreak and 
 passionate affairs\, poverty and wealth\, terrible loss and immense joy. 
 Translated by Frances Riddle.\n\nCopies available at the Circulation Desk 
 starting May 29.\n\n** Participating in the Library World Championship? 
 Chilean author Isabel Allende is one of the most widely read contemporary 
 Spanish-language writers. You can enter Violeta as your Group B title in 
 the championship bracket. **
LOCATION:Literacy Room\, West Orange Public Library
ORGANIZER;CN="West Orange Library":MAILTO:events@westorange.bccls.org
CATEGORIES:Book Club
UID:LibCal-10341-16500073
URL:https://bccls.libcal.com/event/16500073
END:VEVENT
